### 16.2 Measures for Record Maintenance, Preservation, and Reporting (Paragraph 6.2)

The Company shall take the following steps regarding maintenance, preservation, and reporting of client information:

#### 16.2.1 Client Identification Records (Paragraph 6.2(a))

The Company shall maintain and preserve the records pertaining to:

(a) Client identification (including all information and documents obtained under Sections 10 and 11 of this Policy);

(b) Client addresses;

(c) Records obtained during the course of the business relationship.

These records shall be retained for **at least five (5) years after the account-based relationship is ended**.

#### 16.2.2 Transaction Records (Paragraph 6.2(b))

The Company shall maintain and preserve all necessary records of transactions for **at least five (5) years from the date of transaction**.

#### 16.2.3 Records Relating to Ongoing Investigations or Disclosed Transactions (Paragraph 6.2(c))

Where records relate to:

(a) Ongoing investigations; or

(b) Transactions that have been the subject of a disclosure (including STR filings to FIU-IND);

such records shall be retained until it is confirmed that the case has been closed. The five-year retention period does not act as a ceiling in these cases.

Wherever practicable, the Company shall seek and retain relevant identification documents for all such transactions, and shall report any suspicious transactions in accordance with Section 15 of this Policy.

#### 16.2.4 Transaction Reconstruction Capability (Paragraph 6.2(d))

The Company shall maintain all necessary information and records in respect of transactions so as to permit reconstruction of individual transactions. The records shall, at a minimum, capture the following:

(a) **Nature of the transaction:** The type of transaction (e.g., fiat-to-VDA, VDA-to-VDA, VDA-to-fiat, transfer, exchange);

(b) **Amount and types of VDA and/or fiat currency:** The quantum and the specific VDA(s) and/or fiat currencies involved in the transaction;

(c) **Date of transaction:** The date on which the transaction was conducted;

(d) **Parties to the transaction:** The originator, beneficiary, and any other parties to the transaction;

(e) **Travel Rule compliance details:** All originator and beneficiary information required to be obtained, held, or transmitted under Section 13 of this Policy, including PAN, identity document number, name, wallet address, physical address, and date of birth (as applicable).

#### 16.2.5 System for Retention and Retrieval (Paragraph 6.2(e))

The Company shall implement a system with clearly defined procedures for the retention, maintenance, and preservation of all transaction and account records as required under the PMLA, PML Rules, and the 2026 Guidelines.

The system shall enable records and data to be retrieved easily and promptly whenever required or requested by competent authorities, including FIU-IND, law enforcement agencies, and other regulators.

#### 16.2.6 Tamper-Proof Audit Trails (Paragraph 6.2(f))

The Company shall preserve complete audit trails in a tamper-proof manner, including:

(a) **Verification responses** (including OTP validation, penny-drop bank verification, PAN verification, liveness detection, sanctions screening results);

(b) **Timestamps** for all customer-facing events, transaction events, and system access events;

(c) **Authentication logs** capturing user authentication, login events, and access to sensitive records.

The tamper-proof characteristics shall include:

(i) Immutability of audit records once created;

(ii) Cryptographic integrity protection;

(iii) Access logging with role-based controls;

(iv) Regular backup and disaster recovery procedures.

### 16.3 Operational Framework for Record Management

#### 16.3.1 Categories of Records Maintained

The Company shall maintain, at a minimum, the following categories of records:

(a) **Client Onboarding Records:** All KYC documents, supporting documents, liveness verification artifacts, geo-location data, penny-drop verification records, PAN verification records, and onboarding decision documentation;

(b) **Ongoing CDD Records:** All periodic updation records, self-declarations, document refresh records, and risk classification reviews;

(c) **Transaction Records:** Complete records of all transactions executed by the Company on behalf of clients, including counterparty information and Travel Rule data;

(d) **Alert and Investigation Records:** All alerts generated by transaction monitoring, sanctions screening, or other compliance systems; all investigations conducted; and the disposition of each alert;

(e) **STR Records:** Drafts and final versions of STRs filed with FIU-IND, supporting evidence, internal escalation records, and FIU-IND acknowledgements;

(f) **Other Regulatory Reports:** Monthly Reports, NTRs, CTRs (if applicable), Cross-Border Wire Transfer Reports (if applicable), and any other reports filed with FIU-IND or other authorities;

(g) **Section 12A Information Requests:** All requests received from FIU-IND, the responses provided, and supporting documentation;

(h) **Audit and Independent Review Records:** Reports from independent annual audits, internal audits, and other reviews of the AML/CFT/CPF framework, along with remediation tracking;

(i) **Training Records:** Attendance, content, and assessment outcomes for all AML/CFT/CPF training sessions;

(j) **Policy Records:** Version history of this Policy, including approvals and amendments;

(k) **Governance Records:** Board and Board-sub-committee minutes relating to AML/CFT/CPF matters, Risk Assessment outcomes, Risk Classification Framework approvals, and Designated Director and Principal Officer appointment records;

(l) **Sanctions Screening Records:** Records of all sanctions screening events, alert dispositions, and list update events;

(m) **Communications:** Communications with FIU-IND, law enforcement agencies, regulators, and counterparty Reporting Entities relating to AML/CFT/CPF matters.

#### 16.3.2 Retention Periods Summary

| Record Category | Minimum Retention |
|-----------------|---------------------|
| Client identification and address records (after account closure) | 5 years from account closure |
| Transaction records | 5 years from date of transaction |
| Records relating to ongoing investigations or STRs filed | Until case closure (no five-year ceiling) |
| Audit trails (verification responses, timestamps, authentication logs) | Minimum 5 years; longer where supporting an investigation or STR |
| Policy documents and amendments | Permanent (or until superseded plus minimum 5 years) |
| Training records | Minimum 5 years |
| Board minutes relating to AML/CFT/CPF | Permanent or as per applicable corporate retention norms (whichever is longer) |
| Section 12A request responses | Minimum 5 years from response |

The Company may retain records for longer periods where required by applicable law (including tax statutes, corporate law, or sector-specific obligations) or where the Company determines that longer retention is appropriate based on its risk assessment.

#### 16.3.3 Format and Storage

Records shall be stored in:

(a) **Electronic form** as the primary medium, with appropriate cryptographic integrity protection;

(b) **Physical form** where the original document is in physical form, with scanned copies retained electronically;

(c) **Backup storage** with geographic and operational redundancy to ensure availability in the event of a primary system failure;

(d) **Secure access controls** with role-based access and access logging.

#### 16.3.4 Disposal of Records

Upon expiry of the applicable retention period and confirmation that the record is no longer subject to any ongoing investigation, regulatory request, or other extension, records may be disposed of in accordance with the Company's documented record-disposal procedure.

The disposal procedure shall:

(a) Require pre-disposal review by the Principal Officer;

(b) Confirm absence of any retention triggers under Section 16.2.3 above;

(c) Implement secure destruction of physical records and secure deletion of electronic records;

(d) Document each disposal action, including date, scope, and authorisation.

#### 16.3.5 Access to Records by Competent Authorities

The Company shall provide records and information to:

(a) **FIU-IND**, as required under PMLA and PML Rules, including responses to Section 12A requests;

(b) **Law enforcement agencies** including the Enforcement Directorate, in accordance with applicable law;

(c) **Other regulators** with jurisdiction over the Company's operations, including RBI, SEBI, CBDT, and CERT-In, in accordance with applicable law;

(d) **Courts and tribunals**, in accordance with valid legal process.

Access shall be provided within timeframes specified in the relevant request or directive, and the Company shall maintain records of all such access provided.
